* {{IPA|/m, p, b/}} are [[Bilabial consonant|bilabial]], whereas {{IPA|/f, v/}} are [[Labiodental consonant|labiodental]].{{sfnp|Kleine|2003|p=262}}
* The {{IPA|/l – ʎ/}} contrast has collapsed in some speakers.{{sfnp|Kleine|2003|p=262}}
* The palatalized coronals {{IPA|/nʲ, tsʲ, dzʲ, tʃʲ, dʒʲ, sʲ, zʲ/}} appear only in Slavic loanwords.{{sfnp|Kleine|2003|p=262}} The phonemic status of these palatalised consonants, as well as any other affricates, is unclear.
* {{IPA|/k, ɡ, ɣ/}} and {{IPA|[ŋ]}} are [[Velar consonant|velar]], whereas {{IPA|/j, ʎ/}} are [[Palatal consonant|palatal]].{{sfnp|Kleine|2003|p=262}}
** {{IPA|[ŋ]}} is an allophone of {{IPA|/n/}} after {{IPA|/k, ɡ/}}, and it can only be syllabic {{IPA|[ŋ̍]}}.{{sfnp|Kleine|2003|p=262}}
* The phonetic realization of {{IPA|/χ/}} and {{IPA|/nʲ/}} is unclear:
** In the case if {{IPA|/χ/}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Kleine|2003}} puts it in the "velar" column, but consistently uses a symbol denoting a voiceless ''uvular'' fricative {{angbr|{{IPA|χ}}}} to transcribe it. It is thus safe to assume that {{IPA|/χ/}} is phonetically uvular {{IPAblink|χ}}.
** In the case of {{IPA|/nʲ/}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Kleine|2003}} puts it in the "palatalized" column. This can mean that it is either palatalized alveolar {{IPA|[nʲ]}} or alveolo-palatal {{IPAblink|ɲ̟}}. {{IPA|/ʎ/}} may actually also be alveolo-palatal {{IPAblink|ʎ̟}}, rather than just palatal.
* The rhotic {{IPA|/r/}} can be either alveolar or uvular, either a trill {{IPA|[{{IPA link|r}} ~ {{IPA link|ʀ}}]}} or, more commonly, a flap/tap {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɾ}} ~ {{IPA link|ʀ̆}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kleine|2003|p=262}}
* The glottal stop {{IPA|[ʔ]}} appears only as an intervocalic separator.{{sfnp|Kleine|2003|p=262}}

As in the [[Slavic languages]] with which Yiddish was long in [[language contact|contact]] ([[Russian language|Russian]], [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]], [[Polish language|Polish]], and [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]), but unlike [[German language|German]], [[voiceless consonant|voiceless]] stops have little to no [[aspiration (phonetics)|aspiration]]; unlike many such languages, voiced stops are not devoiced in final position.{{sfnp|Kleine|2003|p=262}} Moreover, Yiddish has regressive [[phonation|voicing]] [[assimilation (linguistics)|assimilation]], so that, for example, {{lang|yi|זאָגט}} {{IPA|/zɔɡt/}} ('says') is pronounced {{IPA|[zɔkt]}} and {{lang|yi|הקדמה}} {{IPA|/hakˈdɔmɜ/}} ('foreword') is pronounced {{IPA|[haɡˈdɔmɜ]}}.

==Vowels==
The [[vowel]] phonemes of Standard Yiddish are:

