* {{IPA|/ɪ, ʊ/}} are [[Near-close vowel|near-close]] {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ}}, {{IPA link|ʊ}}]}}, but {{IPA|/ɪ/}} may sometimes be realized as close {{IPAblink|i}}. These allophones are more or less in free variation, but they could have been separate phonemes in the past.{{sfnp|Kleine|2003|p=263}}
* {{IPA|/ɜ/}} appears only in [[stress (linguistics)|unstressed]] syllables.{{sfnp|Kleine|2003|p=263}}

{|class="wikitable"
|+[[Diphthong]]s{{sfnp|Kleine|2003|p=263}}
! Front [[syllable#Nucleus|nucleus]]
! Central nucleus
! Back nucleus
|-
| align=center | {{IPA|ɛɪ}}
| align=center | {{IPA|aɪ}}
| align=center | {{IPA|ɔɪ}}
|}

* The last two diphthongs may be realized as {{IPA|[aɛ]}} and {{IPA|[ɔɜ]}}, respectively.{{sfnp|Kleine|2003|p=263}}

In addition, the [[sonorant]]s {{IPA|/l/}} and {{IPA|/n/}} can function as [[syllable#Nucleus|syllable nuclei]]:
*אײזל  {{IPA|/ˈɛɪzl̩/}} 'donkey'
*אָװנט  {{IPA|/ˈɔvn̩t/}} 'evening'

{{IPA|[m]}} and {{IPA|[ŋ]}} appear as syllable nuclei as well, but only as allophones of {{IPA|/n/}}, after bilabial consonants and [[dorsal consonant]]s, respectively.

The syllabic sonorants are always unstressed.

==Comparison with German==
{{see also|High German consonant shift|Germanic umlaut}}
In vocabulary of Germanic origin, the differences between Standard German and Standard Yiddish pronunciation are mainly in the [[vowel]]s and [[diphthong]]s. Examples are the German long {{IPA|/aː/}} as in ''Vater'' ('father'), which corresponds to {{IPA|/ɔ/}} in Yiddish  {{lang|yi|פֿאָטער}} {{IPA|/ˈfɔtɛr/}}, and the German long {{IPA|/eː/}} and long {{IPA|/oː/}}, which correspond to diphthongs in Yiddish ({{IPA|/ɛɪ/}} and {{IPA|/ɔɪ/}}). As in many Germanic languages, Yiddish lacks the German [[front rounded vowel]]s {{IPA|/œ, øː/}} and {{IPA|/ʏ, yː/}}. They are replaced in Yiddish by {{IPA|/ɛ/}} (in the case of the short {{IPA|/œ/}}), {{IPA|/ɛɪ/}} (in the case of the long {{IPA|/øː/}}) and {{IPA|/ɪ/}} (in the case of {{IPA|/ʏ, yː/}}), respectively.

Diphthongs have also undergone divergent developments in German and Yiddish. Where Standard German has merged the [[Middle High German]] diphthong ''ei'' and long vowel ''ī'' to ''ei'' (pronounced {{IPA|/aɪ/}}), Standard Yiddish has maintained the distinction between them as {{IPA|/ɛɪ/}} and {{IPA|/aɪ/}}, respectively. The German {{IPA|/aʊ/}} (as in ''kaufen'', 'buy') corresponds to the Yiddish {{IPA|/ɔɪ/}} (in  {{lang|yi|קױפֿן}} {{IPA|/kɔɪfn/}}); lastly, the German {{IPA|/ɔʏ/}}, as in ''Deutsch'' 'German') corresponds to {{IPA|/aɪ/}} in Yiddish (in  {{lang|yi|דײַטש}} {{IPA|/daɪtʃ/}}). Another difference is that the [[vowel length]] distinctions of German do not exist in Standard Yiddish.

There are consonantal differences between German and Yiddish. Yiddish [[lenition|deaffricates]] the Middle High German [[voiceless labiodental affricate]] {{IPA|/pf/}} to {{IPA|/f/}} initially (as in {{lang|yi|פֿונט}} ''funt''; though this pronunciation is also quasi-standard throughout northern and central Germany); /pf/ surfaces as an [[High German consonant shift|unshifted]] {{IPA|/p/}} medially or finally (as in {{lang|yi|עפּל}} {{IPA|/ɛpl/}} and {{lang|yi|קאָפּ}} {{IPA|/kɔp/}}). Additionally, final voiced stops appear in Standard Yiddish but not Northern Standard German.

